english:
  title: Epitaph for Minister of Works Kim, Holder of the Rank of Communicating Official
  author: Shin Jong-ho
  language: eng
  text: |-
    My friend Kim Jeol, whose personal name was Hyun, came from a family of prominence. His great-grandfather was Ja-ji, who served as Chamberlain of Kaesong and received the posthumous title Munjeong. His grandfather Hae held the rank of Communicating Official and served as Director of the Bureau of Internal Resources. His father U-sin was a Communicating Official and currently serves as Assessor of the Ministry of Taxation. His mother was of the Lee family, daughter of Yi Gye-chung, Governor of Cheongpung.

    From childhood, Jeol displayed exceptional talent. As he matured, he withdrew from the world to study the classics and histories, so seldom did anyone see his face. Through tireless investigation and boundless inquiry, his understanding deepened with each passing day. In the year Muja, at the age of twenty-one, he achieved first place in the civil service examination. In the year Sinmyo, he again placed first in the advanced examination. His fame blazed across the realm. With his refined bearing and dignified appearance, all who beheld him recognized him as a man of noble character.

    Due to certain circumstances, he remained long without advancement. In the spring of Gyesa, he was appointed as Documenter of the National Academy. That summer he transferred to the position of Junior Officer of the Ministry of War. In Byungsin he received the rank of Holder of Instruction and was given the concurrent position of Keeper of the Record. Shortly after, he was appointed Vice-Rector of the Institute of Letters and concurrently Lecturer at the Royal Lecture Hall. In Jeongyu he received the rank of Holder of Counsel. In Mususuk, when the Institute of Letters was reorganized as the Hongmun Academy, he remained as Vice-Rector and additionally served as Keeper of the Spring and Autumn Annals. In Gihae he received the rank of Bearer of Instruction and was promoted to Rector.

    It was at this time that the state began diplomatic relations with Japan. He was selected as an emissary and dispatched. However, he did not reach his destination and returned. In Gyeongja he received the rank of Bearer of Righteousness and was selected as Examiner of Official Conduct to travel to the Ming court. In Sinchuk he received the rank of Promoter of Harmony. In Imyin he received the rank of Promoter of Virtue, and additionally received the rank of Court Attendant. In Gyemyo he concurrently held the position of Instructor at the Hongmun Academy—a position bestowed upon those of exceptional talent deemed worthy to lead the literary world.

    In Gapjin he received the rank of Holder of Rectitude and was promoted to Director of Studies. In Eulsa he specially received the rank of Middle Instructor. That summer he was elevated to the rank of Communicating Grandee. In Byungoh he was promoted to Assessor of the Ministry of Works, but at this time he fell ill with a wind-borne disease. He requested to resign, but this was not granted. Instead, physicians were sent to treat him. In Jeongmi he again requested to resign, and was transferred to the rank of Senior Guard. Though confined to his sickbed, he continued to receive his stipend. The king frequently inquired after his health and sent him medicines. When he went to bathe at the hot springs of Onyang, the provincial authorities received direct imperial command to dispatch an official palanquin to carry him back—all marks of extraordinary favor. In the first month of Imja, at the age of forty-five, he finally passed from this world. All who heard of it lamented deeply.

    That same year in the third month, he was to be buried in Hubryul Village of Kyoha County, his maternal family's ancestral ground. His elder brother Sim, Assessor of the Ministry of Justice, came to request that I compose this epitaph with great urgency. Could I have the heart to refuse such a request, when my friend has come to this?

    For five years I was acquainted with Jeol in the Bureau of Letters and at the Royal Academy. None knew him better than I. In the year Imyin, through undeserved grace, I came to serve in the inner secretariat. At that time many eminent and extraordinary men of letters gathered there, yet my heart held in reverence none but my friend Jeol alone.

    Once I intended to submit a memorial on affairs of state and spent several days formulating my thoughts. When I brought it to Jeol for his counsel, he smiled softly as if in contemplation. Then, taking up his brush, he swept away my entire composition and ordered fresh paper brought. Like a wind-driven rain that does not pause, his brush flew across the page until within moments several sheets were filled. Observing from the side, I saw how he moved through past and present, how his citations were apt and precise, how his prose sparkled like jewels. Though I, Jong-ho, exhaust the efforts of a lifetime, how could I dare hope to approach even the fringe of his excellence?

    One day, when we presented a matter before the throne, bold words caused the imperial presence to tremble. Those attending shrank back, unable to utter a single sound. But Jeol alone, with calm deliberation, analyzed the matter and turned the royal mind. I was impressed both by his talent and by his steadfast integrity that could not be shaken.

    When he served as emissary to Japan, his ship was caught in storm and wind. The vessel rose and fell like ducks upon the water, and death seemed but a hair's breadth away. All aboard cried out in panic. Yet Jeol sat in serenity, reading his books as though resting in his private chamber. When they reached Tsushima, the chief envoy fell ill and the mission was ordered to return. Everyone rejoiced and leapt with joy, but Jeol alone regretted that he could not venture to the land of the rising sun and exhaust the great wonders of the realm.

    Throughout his life his heart was open and untroubled. He held life and death, gain and loss, as equal before heaven. When confronted with events, nothing could disturb his peace. Had heaven granted him longer years and had he encountered prosperous times, what achievements might he not have accomplished? Yet such is beyond our knowing.

    Alas! Yan Hui died young, and Ran Geng was stricken with illness. Those of wealth and longevity who enjoy all blessings are often those the world regards as base and worthless. What is the reason for this? Does heaven's favor toward the virtuous and punishment of the wicked operate differently from human understanding? Or perhaps in that vast and inscrutable realm, fortune and calamity, gain and loss follow their own nature? We cannot know.

    A man like Jeol—his aging parents still lived, his widow and orphans knew hardship, and his household was bare as wind-swept walls. What sorrow dwelt within those chambers! His prose style was simple, refined, and pure. He was skilled in poetry and especially masterful in regulated verse forms. Even placed among the great poets of antiquity, he would not greatly yield. When the court examined scholars, he invariably took first place, receiving honors and rewards that earned the admiration of all learned men.

    He married the daughter of Yun Chi, former Magistrate of Pyeonggang County, and fathered three sons and three daughters. The eldest son was An-guk, the second An-se, and the third An-ro, all still young. The eldest daughter married the grandson of Shim An-uei, Commandant of Cheongseong. The others remain young.

    The epitaph reads:

    His resolve transcends the frost,
    Steel refined a hundred times.
    His words ascend to heaven,
    Worth ten thousand gold.
    Though the body found no length of years,
    The name shall not decay.
    Through ten thousand ages it endures—
    Why should we grieve?

    Engraved before the tomb,
    It shines for ages to come.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Western Quarters' refers to the quiet precincts of the inner palace administration, a metaphorical reference to the offices of the Bureau of Letters where the author and subject served together.
    - Yan Hui and Ran Geng were celebrated disciples of Confucius known for their virtue; the text laments that wisdom and moral excellence do not protect against early death or illness.
    - The 'land of the rising sun' (Fusang and Changu) refers to Japan, whose full geographic and cultural wonders Jeol never fully witnessed due to the mission's early termination.
